Recently started looking at formly after it popped up on angular weekly.  Fantastic effort on demos and api docs!
What about pipelines to start?  Angular uses them for validators, parsers, formatters, $http, etc.  They could contain functions that transform a presentation schema object into a presentation instance object, enabling custom transformations at any point.
So in the core, something like:
```
var pipelinesToView = {
  presentationSchema:[],// converts presentation schema (i.e., fields) into a custom object we can compile with the html
  presentationInstance:[], // operates on the presentation Instance (for one-off change and performance);
};
// same principle from view to model, including validation, data cleanup, etc.
var pipelinesToModel = {}
```
That would enable a lot of flexibility with a simple imperative API.  It would be possible to add plugins for things like 'repeat' by adding/removing functions in the pipelines.
for example:
formly.addPlugin('repeater',function(pipelines){
  pipelines.presentationSchema.push(
    function repeater(presentationInstance){
      // recursively walks over each part of the presentation schema as "this"
      for(var i=0; i < this.repeats; i++){
        presentationInstance.children.push(clone(this.children[0]))
      }
      return this;
    }
  );
});
Could go with html and controller like:
```
// html


// controller
$scope.model ={};
$scope.presentationInstance = {};
$scope.presentationSchema = {
  fields:[{
    key:'customField',
    type:'text',
    placeholder:'foo',
    repeats:2  // <--- repeater would operate on this
  }]
};
```
Dynamically appending pipeline functions would enable sophisticated conditions, though managing conflicts would need to be resolved
$scope.presentationSchema = {
  fields:[{
    type:'button',
    events:{
      click:function(event,presentationInstance,pipelines){
        if(presentationInstance.children > 2){
          pipelines.presentationSchema.push(function(){
            // add some conditional display logic
          });
          queuePipelineExecution();
        }
      }
    }
  }]
};
The same architecture would make it possible to implement something like the json schema in #147 by prepending transformations to the pipelines
